To get a reaction from a message in Discord.js, you can use the `awaitReactions()` or `createReactionCollector()` methods.

Here's an example using `awaitReactions()`:

```js
// First, get the message you want to react to
const message = await channel.send('React to this message!');

// Add a reaction to the message
await message.react('❤️');

// Wait for a reaction to be added
const filter = (reaction, user) => reaction.emoji.name === '❤️' && user.id !== client.user.id;
const collector = message.createReactionCollector(filter, { time: 15000 });

collector.on('collect', (reaction, user) => {
  console.log(`${user.tag} reacted with ${reaction.emoji.name}`);
});

collector.on('end', collected => {
  console.log(`Collected ${collected.size} reaction(s)`);
});
```

Here's an example using `createReactionCollector()`:

```js
// First, get the message you want to react to
const message = await channel.send('React to this message!');

// Add a reaction to the message
await message.react('❤️');

// Create a reaction collector
const filter = (reaction, user) => reaction.emoji.name === '❤️' && user.id !== client.user.id;
const collector = message.createReactionCollector(filter, { time: 15000 });

collector.on('collect', (reaction, user) => {
  console.log(`${user.tag} reacted with ${reaction.emoji.name}`);
});

collector.on('end', collected => {
  console.log(`Collected ${collected.size} reaction(s)`);
});
```

Both of these examples will listen for users reacting with the ❤️ emoji on the message, and will log a message when a reaction is added. The collector will end after 15 seconds, and will log the total number of reactions collected.

